  "doi": "10.1172/jci85679",
  "title": "Hotspot autoimmune T cell receptor binding underlies pathogen and insulin peptide cross-reactivity.",
  "journal": "The Journal of clinical investigation",
  "year": 2016,
  "authors": "Cole DK, Bulek AM, Dolton G, Schauenberg AJ, Szomolay B, Rittase W, Trimby A, Jothikumar P, Fuller A, Skowera A, Rossjohn J, Zhu C, Miles JJ, Peakman M, Wooldridge L, Rizkallah PJ, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "A human CD8+ T cell clone (1E6) derived from a type-1-diabetes patient was studied using high-resolution crystal structures of its T cell receptor bound to seven altered peptide ligands derived from preproinsulin and pathogenic peptides, all presented on MHC class I. The TCR achieves remarkable multiligand recognition\u2014engaging over 1 million different peptides\u2014through a conserved \"hotspot\" binding footprint that permits extensive sequence variation outside this critical contact region, with binding energetics shifting from enthalpy-dominated (weak, self-peptide) to entropy-dominated (strong, pathogen-derived peptide) interactions. This structural mechanism reveals how a single TCR can recognize both a weak self-antigen (insulin) and potent pathogen-derived peptides with altered affinities, explaining how molecular mimicry and cross-reactivity between microbial and self-antigens may break self-tolerance and precipitate autoimmune disease in type 1 diabetes.",
 "noncanonical": {
  "flag": false,
  "evidence": ""
 },
